# /etc/udev/rules.d/99-tablet-mode.rules
#
# Inspiron 7786 tablet-mode signaling — empirically traced 2026-04-29.
# See docs/tablet-mode-investigation.md for the full hardware capture
# (kernel logs, evtest output, sysfs dump). Summary:
#
# - The 7786's ACPI device is INT33D5, claimed by the `intel_hid`
#   driver. `intel_vbtn` is a different driver matching INT33D6 only;
#   it doesn't load on this laptop. Any older comment that says vbtn
#   produces these events here is wrong — they come from intel_hid.
# - At boot, intel_hid creates two static input devices under
#   /devices/platform/INT33D5:00/: "Intel HID events" and
#   "Intel HID 5 button array". Neither advertises EV_SW —
#   capabilities/sw=0 on both. A rule keying on "Intel HID events"
#   with SW_TABLET_MODE will never fire.
# - The first time the screen folds back, the kernel **dynamically
#   creates a new input device** named "Intel HID switches" with
#   EV=0x21 (SYN+SW) and SW=0x2 (bit 1 = SW_TABLET_MODE). It persists
#   for the rest of the boot. On the first fold udev sees this as
#   ACTION=add with ENV{SW_TABLET_MODE}=1 already populated; on every
#   subsequent transition udev sees ACTION=change with the new value.
#
# Hence two rules below — one for add, one for change — both keyed on
# the device name, both gated on ENV{SW_TABLET_MODE} being set so we
# don't trip on unrelated events on the same device.
#
# Why we write to a state file instead of running hyprctl directly:
#   - udev runs as root with no Wayland/Hyprland env. Calling hyprctl
#     from here would need a wrapper that finds WAYLAND_DISPLAY +
#     HYPRLAND_INSTANCE_SIGNATURE and `runuser` into tom — fragile
#     across login sessions, and breaks at the greeter.
#   - Instead: we write the new SW_TABLET_MODE bit to
#     /run/tablet-mode/state. A user-level systemd path unit
#     (~/.config/systemd/user/tablet-mode-watch.path) watches that
#     file and triggers tablet-mode.service, which inherits the user
#     session env and runs hyprctl with full context.
#
# The mkdir -p cost of doing this on every event is negligible (<1ms),
# and the unconditional `printf` keeps the rule branch-free.
#
# Verify on real hardware:
#   sudo udevadm monitor --environment --subsystem-match=input
#   (fold once: ACTION=add with NAME="Intel HID switches",
#    SW_TABLET_MODE=1; fold back: ACTION=change with =0)

ACTION=="add",    SUBSYSTEM=="input", ATTRS{name}=="Intel HID switches", ENV{SW_TABLET_MODE}=="?*", \
    RUN+="/bin/sh -c 'mkdir -p /run/tablet-mode && printf %%s %E{SW_TABLET_MODE} > /run/tablet-mode/state && chmod 0644 /run/tablet-mode/state'"
ACTION=="change", SUBSYSTEM=="input", ATTRS{name}=="Intel HID switches", ENV{SW_TABLET_MODE}=="?*", \
    RUN+="/bin/sh -c 'mkdir -p /run/tablet-mode && printf %%s %E{SW_TABLET_MODE} > /run/tablet-mode/state && chmod 0644 /run/tablet-mode/state'"
